procedure: It was a remarkable experience to be at the top of this ladder after our 5-year reunion. I was never anywhere near this kind of social standing when I was a student; of course, I loved my time as a student, but never did I have so much influence and respect from people I barely knew. It feels somewhat uncomfortable, just because I am not used to being in such a position, but it is a satisfying feeling nonetheless. It proves to me that my hard work has paid off.
After seeing my old friends and classmates I feel as if they had not changed their perspectives of me at all since our last encounters.
I would definitely be very confident in the things I am saying and doing. I think I would feel as if I was slightly better than the people around me.
I would feel very powerful and respected. I would probably feel like I had a lot of influence, like everyone knew about me, and would have a good time at the reunion.

If I was at the top of the latter I would feel very proud of myself and like I really accomplished a lot in life. I wouldnt act superior to everyone else though although deep down I might feel like it
I would feel very accomplished and that I have done a lot better than the rest of my peers.

I would feel very pleased with myself. I think having others look up to me would feel good. I would probably act a bit more entitled than I do now. My thinking process would be different because I would not be so concerned about how others perceived me.

I would look for those at the bottom of the ladder and would understand that you need to get outside of yourself and help other people in order to help yourself. This has been mentality has arisen due to personal experience

I attended my 5-year college reunion for the Class of 2024 yesterday. Everyone that I graduated with is pretty well off, and it was really cool to hear all that everyone had accomplished. I wanted to talk about my accomplishments as well, but I didn't want to come off as a bragger. I kept a lot of it to myself, unless someone asked me to share what I have been doing and what successes I've had. I felt good knowing that I was doing well in life, although I did find myself comparing my life to theirs. However, I know that I am well respected in my field and I don't need validation from others, but it gave me a confidence boost to know I am on the right track and doing well.

Being at the top of the ladder means that I've not only been highly successful academically and have maintained high achievement scholastically, but also that I am very socially adept. To be at the top rung I have impressed a variety of different groups with different values. TO an extent I am an every man, but also someone who is looked up to for a multitude of different reasons. I am the life of the party yet not unapproachable or intimidating. My current job shows my continued trajectory for success proving to on lookers that their perception of me is well founded. I feel comfortable and calm at all times and seek out the fun in any situation. I look for how I connect to others and emphasize the relation to foster close relationships. I make each individual who I interact with feel special and listened to.  a

Yesterday, I went to my 5 year college reunion. It was really nice to catch up with everyone and see people I haven’t seen in years. People told me they had heard about some of my accomplishments but I don’t like to brag. It was nice to be recognized by a lot of people.

I honestly don't think I would act much different wherever I was on the ladder. I'm definitely not perfect but I do think humility is a strength of mine, and if I did happen to be highly respected, I still wouldn't consider myself better than anyone else there.
I would feel great If i were at the top of the ladder because I would feel like I had an influence and change on my expeirence as well as others.
I have done very well for myself. My hard work has paid off. I also got really lucking I picked the right carear.

I arrived at my 5-year college reunion at around 2. Wow. It's been 5 years. 5 years since the best time in my life. As I expected, my past friends immediately came up to me to talk and reconnect. It had been a while since I was in contact with my fraternity brothers, so it was great to see them again. People came up to talk to me whom I didn't even remember, but they said that we had a math class together or something. There were too many people at this school for me to remember, but they all remember me.

Success in the form of money, pride, or don’t determine my happiness. It comes with maintaining a good mental health, so I am not sure how I’d feel at the top of the ladder. It all depends on whether or not I’ve been taking care of myself.

I think that I would treat people the same I do now, but I would use my power to influence people to change their habits for the better. Mainly in regards to drug use, as well as plastic consumption and environmentalism.
I walked in feeling proud and knowing that everyone would remember me. In that moment I felt powerful.
I will be proud of myself. Simultaneously, I will examine my peers' social status and ask myself what is the key to success. Also, I will try to act normal, as if I have not changed a lot.

Very happy, I would talk to a lot of people. I would try and see how everyone else is doing. I would definitely try and talk about my job and be friendly with most people. I would stay a long time and probably go out with some old friends after
I feel like I am better than everyone else, I look down upon people at the bottom of the ladder.

If I was at the top of the ladder five years out of college I would be confident. I would carry myself with a sense of pride and respect knowing that I am doing well.  I would probably be happy and mentally all there. I wouldn't be stressed or worried about much.

I attended my 5-year college reunion. Everyone seems to be doing well, and in great points in their life carreer wise, however they are still too focused on getting money and not appreciating life. There's so much more to life then all of that. Even though I am very established, I understand these concepts.
I would feel that all my hard work paid off but I would not be satisfied because there is still much more work to do

If I were to be at the top of the ladder at my 5-year college reunion, I would probably feel very similar to my peers. Everyone around me has access to wealth and education, I would simply just feel proud of myself.

I was excited to see all of the people that I was friends with in college. It was awesome to see where everyone ended up. It was crazy how many people I remembered. I am very glad that everyone is doing well for themselves.
I think I would be very confident and proud as I looked back on all I accomplished and saw friends again.

If it was at the top of the ladder i know that i would have had a positive impact to the people around me. I would have inspired others to be the best versions of themselves. my own achievements would make me respected by others. I would want to have been viewed as a kind, respectful, hardworking and successful person.

I would be very proud of myself because I graduated from Wake and that I have graduated from law school. I would definetly feel quite relieved because my life would be more planned out by then and a lot more predictable.
I would feel a great deal achievement for the time I've spent working at my craft.

I feel confident and happy.  I love being in the limelight for a good reason.  Inside, I feel warm and accepted.  I feel like I am a really important part of WF who cannot be replaced, and as a result I pay attention to how I am acting and how I make people feel.  I know a lot of eyes are on me, so this is not the time to mess up.  I  smile and reach out to everyone I remember from college, even if we weren't good friends.  I want them to feel as accepted to me.  I laugh and joke the whole time, and try to catch up with my peers to see if they are doing anything as impressive as me.

I believe I would make a lot of friends at Wake and I wouldn't be able to wait to see them again. Can see myself saying hi to so many people, in hopes to put a smile on their face. I'd also be sure to remember each and every name! I'd want to catch up with everybody that I can asking them how their life has been after Wake.
I would feel really good about where I am

I feel on top of the world right now. I'm feeling so blessed to have been able to go back and talk with the people I spent undergrad with as a successful business woman. I feel so proud of my accomplishments and am excited to see where I can go in the next ten years.
i think i would feel very good about myself going into a reunion. would probably confidently shake hands and hug the people i went to college w and be proud to talk about my career

I would imagine that people were very interested in my life's story, what i had done in the five years since they'd last seen me. They'd be curious about what I'd been involved in and what I'm doing now. I think I would act and feel very proud and dignified. I would feel as though the effort I put into school, relationships and extracurricular activities paid off and allowed me to become the person that people admire, listen to, and want to be friends with.
I would speak to my peers as peers regardless of placement on a ladder. If position is in mind, the beholder is shallow.

Ideally, I would imagine myself as a happy yet mature and professional woman with a job that I love. I would also have a family and kids, and I would have close relationships with my siblings and parents.

Today, I went back to Wake Forest to visit all of my friends and professors at the reunion. It felt good to have people remember my name and ask about how my current research was coming along. It was a lot of pressure to meet so many people and I felt guilty that I didn't remember all of their names. There is also a sort of anxiety feeling that you've peaked in life and wondering if you've deserved all you've come to have.
probably I'll still listen to others' speakings, but have no idea what they're talking about their lives and disagree with them, probably even look down on them but without showing it.
At that time, I would think in a macro perspectives and act more calmly toward things and feel more relaxed.

If I was at the top of the ladder, I feel like I would feel really successful, and have a good job and be doing well financially. I would wonder where everyone else is on the ladder, and wonder how I got to the top. I would not act any different being on the top of the ladder.
I would feel accomplished and proud of myself that I have done enough in 5 years that I can see myself in such a positive light in reference to all of Wake Forest. all of

Being in a stable job and doing well for myself, I would feel wealthy and secure. I would dress well, have many friends and social opportunities, and spend a good deal of money. I would probably think highly of myself and think down on others at times. Overall, if I had been at the very top of the ladder while at Wake and beyond, I would have felt great about myself but probably also felt less concerned with the needs and welfare of others. I would become somewhat arrogant and conceited, and even discontent as well.
I feel like I made the right choice of what school to go and what I decided to do with my life. I have no regrets and feel proud of where I have come from and where I am today.
I will feel confident

I am proud to have succeeded and reached the top.  I am proud and grateful for the education I was given at WFU.  Although I do not wish the downfall on others, I am happy that I rose above these students.  I am proud my efforts went above the level of complacency I remember these students having when I went to school with them.  It was a lot of work to reach this point but, I think it was worth the results.

If I were on top of the ladder, I’d be sure to climb down from it. I’d make sure people knew I was there, but I wouldn’t rub it in. I’d try to show them we are all equals. Id treat everyone with respect. And it would shock them how I am where they were, and I nicer than they were.

Dear Diary, after attending my 5 year college reunion of my graduation class of 2025 from Wake Forest University, I've learned that I have succeeded many of my peers in career endeavors. I believe that, despite our accomplishments, many of us were put on the campus of Wake to work together in achieving similar goals not only for ourselves, but for our community. The mission we lived by and still stand on today, were and are valuable to our lives and made an impact on how we viewed the world. I believe that we were all selected and agreed to be apart of the Wake Forest Community for a reason, and we all ended up where we were supposed to be. Though we aren't all the wealthiest or most successful, we have impacted each other and left marks that were memorable for us and will be for years to come. Wherever we stand individually geographically, socio-economically, and in many other positions in life, we are where we are supposed to be and I'm confident that we all live content knowing that we not only received quality interdivisional education, but in the meanwhile we were able to create and impact our community and this impact continues to live on through us in our everyday lives.
I went to my college reunion earlier, it is crazy how old I feel right now. Apparently I am one of the more successful people out of my class, that is weird to think about.

First off, I would behave humbly at the top of the ladder.  I would not make it known that I am doing the absolute best, but rather focus on reuniting with my friends. I would feel very grateful at this reunion because it would remind me of the buildings blocks that got me to the top of the ladder.

To be at the top of the ladder would mean that I could act in response to my impulses without worrying as much about the cost (financial, physical, emotional, etc.). I would feel power-hungry, since it would be harder for those on the ladder below me to speak up against me when I make a decision. I wouldn't consider myself a selfish person, but with the benefits that come with being at the top of the ladder, I could think and make decisions based off of my personal interests.

I would feel very confident in myself and proud at my accomplishments. I would be very proud at myself for all my hard work at Wake Forest and be very thankful to all the people that got me to where I was now. People including my parents, professors, friends, and family. I would want to reach out to my colleagues of my class and continue to expand my network. In all, I would feel overjoyed and extremely happy at where I was in life. However, the day after I might also feel pressure to stay at the top of the ladder. This pressure might cause me stress and anxiety to continue being at the top. All in all, I would feel overjoyed that I’m at the top of the ladder.
I would feel confident in myself and proud of my accomplishments. I would feel excited to share them with my peers from wake.

I would be someone that people look up to and that they can go to me for help and emotional support if they need to. In addition, I would be a hard working student who has achieved a lot in my educational career both inside and outside the class.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would feel honored that I was able to influence, help, and serve such a big and great community. I wouldn't look down upon the people who would "be at the bottom of the ladder", instead I would help them raise up the ladder. Wake Forest is a community that I am glad I am apart of and I am more than happy to mold and help others achieve their dreams as well.
If I were at the top of the ladder I would feel accomplished and grateful for a college that provided me with skills to obtain the top of the ladder.
at the top of the ladder, I feel confident and grateful for my time at wake forest. It has shaped me to be a well respected alumni who has achieved all goals set in my time at the university.

Seeing my class again at the 5year reunion was a rewarding experience. I am proud of myself of all my hard work to get where I am, and great-full for how the wake forest and the people there helped me get to where I am. .

If I were at the top of the Wake Forest ladder at my 5-year reunion, I would hope to love and be loved by those around me. I would hope to have a GENUINE and truly good reputation among my classmates in which I feel known and seen and able to do the same for others. I would hope to have a strong degree from my four years at Wake and hopefully be doing something impactful with it.

Today was my 5 year reunion and I loved getting to catch up with my old classmates. It is so interesting to see what everyone has ended up doing with their lives. I have nothing but respect for my classmates who are following their goals and dreams, whatever that may be. I know some people did not end up as well as me after college, but as long as they are happy that is all that matters.
I would feel like I live a much better Iife than people from my class. I have chosen a career that suits me the most. I will also feel lucky that I’ve chosen a better path.
NA

If I was at the top of the ladder after a 5-year college reunion I would treat everyone with respect and hold myself to a high standard. I wouldn't think of myself as being above people and I would try to help out those who are in need.
Dear journal, yesterday I went to my 5-year college reunion and encountered a lot of people who I thought would never see again. It's funny to see how a lot of them succeeded. I'm so happy for them!
I will feel welcomed but kind of stressed.

I am a dentist with a successful practice in Nashville and I am married. I would feel super confident at the reunion and I would not feel discourage or our of place. I would feel proud of my accomplishments and content. I am not super competitive, so I would not care about my place compared to others.
I don't think I would act any different. I don't want to change with success, power, influence, money, etc. I expect myself to act the same way.

After attending my reunion, I feel proud of myself for being looked upon so highly.  I take a great deal of pride in how hard I have worked and my accomplishments, while still being a kind, thoughtful, and positive person.
I have a wonderful group of friends, I have a good job, I am happy
I will feel so confident with everything I do.

I would try and be humble and not act too full of myself while there. I am proud of myself that of all of the huge class of smart intelegent people I was doing the best. My ego would i'm sure be through the roof and I would probably be judgemental of those who were not near as successful as I had been
I feel grateful, as many of my peers should as well. We have made It so far from where we were and I am proud of everyone, and very proud of myself.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would feel confident and proud of what I have accomplished. I would be in either a masters program or pursuing my dream job. I would be excited and ready to take on the future.

I would feel as though I had succeeded in life, surrounded by other successful people but still being one of the best. I also might feel somewhat superior if I knew that I had done one of the best of my class. I don't think that I would act very different than I had when I first graduated, although interactions with someone at the bottom of the latter might feel more awkward than they had when we graduated.

Everyone came up and talked to me, I expected that because most people know who I am in the class.  I like that everyone knows who I am.  People are nice to me for the most part but also know others have their opinions.  I worked really hard to have this respect from my peers, it's nice to still have it 5 years after graduation.  A lot of people are just as successful as me.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would feel encouraged and supported by my alma mater. I would feel fulfilled in my experience and proud of the influence I had on my school and college community. I would ultimately feel quite proud of myself.

I would feel proud and accomplished, but it wouldn't make me feel any different or superior than the people I was seeing at the reunion. I would also just be excited to see people, and who they've become.
I feel as though I have exceeded the level most post-graduates arrive at and I am lucky to be in such a posititon

If I was at the top of this ladder at this time, I would imagine that I had risen quickly through the ranks of a future employer. due to the fast nature of my career, I'm assuming I'd be a leader and an example to follow. Being that this is a personal goal of mine, I'd feel satisfied and eager for more.

If I were to be at the top I would have one of the better paying jobs at the time. Possible in law somewhere in a big city where I have some influence. My classmates may not remember me from school but they will remember me now because of my success after college. It feels good to finally be placed on the map and those who did nothing but party in school be at the bottom.

I think if I were at the top of the ladder I would hold myself with more confidence and be extremely calm and humble because I have nothing to prove to these people. I would also feel a sense of superiority because I would have taken my wake forest education and been able to take it further than other people.

If I were at the top of the ladder I would expect that I got involved in a lot of clubs and community service during my time as an undergraduate student. I would also expect that I made a lot of life long relations and connections which allowed me to thrive academically, eventually leading to a good job. I would also expect that to be on the top I would have a lot of times still connected to the university through multiple facets.

I feel very successful now years after graduation, I have a lot of friends and my job supplies me with lots of money. I also really enjoy my job, school helped me to figure out where I wanted to take my future. I am very thankful for everyone and everything that helped me get to this place in my life because honestly I wasn't sure if I would ever make it here because of previous doubts about what I wanted to do and how many people I would meet that would help me along the way. I'm feeling very grateful right now and happy that I was able to reunite with my friends years after graduation.
Confident, greeting everyone as if I knew them, treating each person as important, you'd think everyone knows who you are

8/23- Went to my 5 year college reunion yesterday. I woke up today and found myself remising on what a wonderful time I had there. I mean a lot of these people are still some of my best friends and I am thrilled to still have them around.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would probably think that I am better than the rest of my former classmates, but I would instantly feel badly about my thoughts. I would try to act humbly and talk to all of my classmates about their endeavors, but I might feel a little bit out of place.

I used to think that social interaction controlled your life. But after I graduated I realized that education and family are more important that I originally thought, and it only took me 5 years to realize that. I still hope to help my college peers succeed, even if they did not help me in the past.

Yesterday was the 5 year wake college reunion. It was weird seeing how different everyone was and what they had done in their time after wake. I myself am glad that I used my years in college to prepare myself for where I am now. Not many other people could say that they are similar to me at the reunion. I feel a sense of pride. Who wouldn't being the highest earning attorney this soon after graduating. I hope that in the future my peers can be as successful as me in their future. I also hope that they can be as happy as me. I'm currently married to an NFL player living in the suburbs of Nashville and I don't think life could get any better than this.

Dear Journal, today is the day after your 5 year reunion at Wake Forest. Looking around the room you compared yourself to others. What jobs others had, how much money others were making and how your life compared to theirs. You were at the top. You made it. You can confidently say that you are the most successful. You have one of the highest paying jobs in the medical field and all the respect in the world for Wake Forest and where it got you today. but, your heart aches for the classmates that weren't as successful as you were. The classmates who's education is going to waste. You are happy and thankful for where your life has gone but part of you wishes everyone could have been successful.

I attended my college reunion yesterday. I was so excited to see how everyone else turned out. I was not too nervous, and I felt comfortable in the room. I tried to talk to as many people as I could to see how they were doing.
If I were at the top of the ladder I hope that I have a job in law that I love and I in a relationship that could lead to marriage.

Dear Journal, today is the day I will finally see my classmates all together for the first time in 5 years. I wonder what they will think of my new company? Will they look up to me? Will they want advice? Do they have companies? I am a little bit nervous because I do not know where everyone ended up, but I would like to think everyone is successful after attending Wake Forest.
If I were at the top of the ladder I would feel confident but not cocky. I would go to this reunion excited because of my status but I wouldn't flaunt it upon people.
I feel accomplished and valued in my community
I would act the same as I do now. Nothing changes as I become successful. The only difference is I likely know/am known by far more people so I speak with more people

I would feel good, hopefully being confident in myself. It is nice to have good two way chemistry with those around you, and I feel you would have the best and most enjoyable experience with that at the top of the ladder.
I am about to get marriage and become a vice manager of my department

If I was at the top of the ladder, I would feel proud of myself for having accomplished what I wanted my goals. By this time I would like to be in first year of residency as a doctor. I wouldn't necessarily think that I was better than other people, but I would feel better about myself knowing that I am doing well in life.

If I were at the top of the ladder in 5 years, it would be because people admire and respect many aspects about the way I live (my achievements, my work ethic, how I approach working with others). If I have earned this level of respect, it will be because I respect others. I think I would believe myself to be considerate and diligent in my work, as well as passionate. I think I would feel proud of my achievements and the recognition, but would not change much about the way I act now, other that being more mature and confident.
I will feel so confident and amazing about myself. I'd still likely to act humbly and politely.

I feel like I would be ahead of my peers or on another plane. I would hope this would lead me not to be arrogant or snobby, but I could see this happening to lots of people. I believe I would try to talk to other people about what they do rather than myself. However, on the inside I would be comparing them to myself.
The joy I feel is overwhelming. I have all I have ever dreamed of. Seeing others around me and their success has allowed me to see how successful and blessed I am.
I would feel very proud and respected by my colleagues. I do not believe that I would flaunt my success or wealth.

It was the best day, every person teacher and student knew me by name and said hi to me. There was not constantly a moment where I wasn't talking to a fellow classmate. They all spoke about how they followed me on socials with envy of my job, lifestyle, apartment, etc. I felt so desired and important, it is going to be hard to go back to the big city. Any nerves I held in college diminished I walked around with total confidence. I felt important but sorry for fellow classmates that had to live vicariously through me.
I would feel superior to my classmates. I would act humble however because I still value humility no matter how much "status" you may have.

It feels so good to have been able to experience everything that I did during my time at Wake Forest. Having seen all of the people that journeyed beside me flourish into full-grown adults was incredible. I'm so proud of everything I accomplished during my time at Wake, and being back with these people again made me feel like I was a freshman all over again.

I would probably feel pretty elitist. I would be proud of my accomplishments. I might look down upon others who did not achieve similar levels of success. I would be happy to see my old friends and would hope that they saw similar success to me.
NA

I show up to my college reunion married and having just begun my medical residency after completing medical school. People at the reunion remember me and are excited to see me, and I have kept in touch with a lot of my friends from college. I am not boastful or prideful about where I am at, rather I am able to focus on other people's lives and learn more about what they've experienced since graduating.

I think I would not change that much, I would still try to find out more about where other people are than talk about myself. However I would definitey feel proud since this is not neccesairy how I feel at this moment at wake.

I never could have gotten to the established position I am in without the help of the staff, faculty, and my peers. The ideals of this university as being humanity centered helped better my own ideas of what it means to help people. I saw those at the reunion and was filled with a sense of pride at what all they had accomplished in such a short time. I also felt honored in my own right for being among them when the time came to graduate, that we had studied, struggled, but ultimately overcame adversity together.

If I was at the top place on the latter, I think I would feel extremely happy with myself. Everyone would love and respect me, I have an amazing job where I am able to make a lot of money and also do what I am passionate about, helping people. I am glad that my hard work and dedication has paid off. I do not think I would try to act as if I was above anyone else, as I know how terrible it is when people do that to me, and how it makes me lose respect in them.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would feel unstoppable. I would feel extremely confident coming back to my college reunion. I would probably act very important like my life and career were very meaningful, or better than others. I would dress to impress.
Wake forest is awesome. I enjoyed every moment, and built lifelong friendships. I would want to make wake more accessible to the community and people who are not from wealth families though.
I would just be and act as myself, because my work and respective accomplishments can speak for themselves. I don't have anything to prove.
I think it would be fun to run into your friends and be able to demonstrate that you did what you had intended to do.

I returned to Wake Forest five years after graduation to my peers who I influenced and inspired while at Wake. Many professors recognize me, as do many of my old classmates. I don't remember all of their names and faces, but treat them with kindness in hopes that I will.

I felt better than everyone else. Feel like I worked much harder than everyone else to be in the position I am in. I know there are lots of accomplished people around me but I would feel and act like I was better than them.

If I were at the top of the ladder, I would assume I would have had to do something pretty noteworthy to get there. At the reunion, if I knew people knew what I did and how successful I was, I think I might feel a bit embarrassed. I would not want those successes to define who I am as a person, which I think they might if I had not seen these people in so long. If that was not the case, then I would try to go about it very normally, like how I would if that was not the case.

I would feel happy to have seen all of my friends and classmates. I would act the same as everyday and try to be nice and supportive to everyone. I would think about everyone I got to see again and about where they are now.

I imagine being at the top of the ladder is a rewarding feeling, especially even after 5 years. It shows that you had a positive impact on many of those around you, which would definitely make me feel good about the choices I made to get where I am. Moreover, it would make me want to continue being who I am because it shows me that what I did throughout my 4 years at Wake Forest was enough to have a meaningful impact on someone else. I think knowing that what you did has changed someone-- even if it was just by brightening up their day-- is the most special and rewarding feeling you can experience.
I would feel as though I am superior to my peers and that my hard work during college were worth while.

If I were very admired at wake forest university, I would talk with everyone and try and be very kind/welcoming. I would have been a very active part of the community and had deep connections with a lot of people

After seeing my old classmates today, I feel kind of superior knowing that I am at the top of the ladder amongst them. A lot of the boys in my class made me feel smaller than my worth in college and it was nice to almost feel a sense of revenge and satisfaction knowing that I earn more than them and I'm happier too.

The connections that I was able to make through attending Wake Forest and participating in a variety of clubs and organizations has allowed me to accomplish all that I had dreamed of, and has given me confidence and high hopes for my future. Through the internship opportunities I was offered, I have been able to collaborate with very knowledgeable people who have made me realize my passions.

I feel extremely lucky for the opportunities that Wake gave me and am so fortunate for how it has helped my life. I am now working an extremely successful job that not only makes good money, but is something that I truly enjoy and makes me feel fulfilled. I loved getting to see my old classmates who were also an influence on how I got to where I am now. I would not be as happy as I am without the experiences I went through at Wake, both good and bad.
I would be proud of myself for my success, likely due to the success of my start-up that I created in college. I would be modest and make conversation with my good friends.

I feel accomplished and proud. I am very rich, influential, popular, and well known. I have achieved many/all of my goals, and I am where I want to be in life. I am very happy, emotional, and a little bit exhausted.

It was amazing to attend the five-year reunion yesterday. I was able to reconnect with so many of my fellow students who I worked hand in hand with to better the Wake Forest community. I feel so honored to have graduated with such a wonderful class. I have so much respect for my fellow graduated and feel so proud of the hard work we have put in to get where we are in life. I admire each and every one of the graduates. I really enjoyed seeing so many people who knew me and understood my past and current accomplishments. I think people know how hard I worked to get involved on campus because so many people thanked me for my impact on the campus.
I would walk around saying hi to everyone I knew and be excited to come back. I would be proud of what I had accomplished and think I am the man.

If I was in the top place on the ladder I would feel happy and proud of all that I accomplished and be very excited and humbled to have received the honor of my peers. I would feel great about myself in this position.
I would be humble, saying hi to old friends and if I was better off financially, taking friends out for dinner etc
I would feel very successful if I were at the top place on the ladder because I would be respected and admired by my peers. I would act confident and sure of myself.

At my 5 year reunion I feel nothing but grateful for everything I have been given in life. Because of the school I was able to achieve what I wanted in life but also become the person I had always looked up to as a child.

I would think of myself very highly if I were at the top place on the ladder, yet I'd still be very aware of where I came from and who I was before I was even close to the top.  I'd try and act the same because I don't think position is an excuse for bad behavior but I would feel stronger about my place in the world and hopefully that would mean something to me.
I am still study for my doctorate. By the way, I am also having a job in business. I am normal but I can get lots of fun by myself. I rent a house and I live in NYC.
I will feel accomplished and invincible.

I believe I would be very thankful for my experience at wake that kickstarted my amazing life! I think I would also be very happy to have seen everyone at the reunion and also proud to show my peers that I ended up doing just great! :)
I feel as if Wake Forest prepared me greatly for where I stand today, I honestly did not expect to see myself like this compared to other classmates.
I would feel euphoric as I have finally achieved my dreams and aspirations of success.
At first, I would likely be in disbelief. I would then feel very accomplished and proud of my achievements. I think I would become more outgoing, because I would feel a surge in confidence

If I were to attend a reunion at the top of a ladder of respect, likely due to post-graduation success, I would hope that I would continue to treat everyone the same way I had before, and be equally respectful to them. Furthermore, I would hope that somehow, my own success would allow me to help out some of my closest friends along the way.
embarrassed, sad, nervous, anxious
I would not have a stable job or living environment. I would feel embarrassed at the reunion
I would think that maybe there are some unique aspect of my life that all my knowledge from college will become worthy one day.
I would act very shy, nervous, anxious, and worrying about how people percieve me
I probably do not know anyone, do not have any close friends, living life alone and doing my own thing or even not be able to complete my own task appropriately
Disappointed. Depressed with such a failure, wasted opportunity, and difficult future ahead.
I frankly wouldn't care too much, it wouldn't really affect me as long as i was doing what I thought to be right.
I would feel pretty isolated. Being at the bottom would mean that not many people would know me and I wouldn't have a real place at the reunion.

I felt very out of place attending the 5-year reunion. It seems as though everyone had their lives together with the perfect jobs, relationships, and overall standing in life. I feel so behind after hearing about all of their success. I still have so much work to do.

Wake Forest is a home to many. To me, it’s feels more like a workplace. Nothing much of note to me, just classes and faces that are unimportant. Going to class, doing work, going to bed, and waking up and repeating every day. My only solace is the few friends I have, and I am content with the few relationships I have. I haven’t strived for the popularity or admiration from the student body like others around me, I only wanted to do what I need to in trying to make it out.

Here at my time at Wake Forest, I acted in a way that has left a negative impression on my classmates. I was rude, cheated, wasted the time of my professors and stabbed many people in the back. No one bothers to keep up with me so I have very little respect or admiration.
I suppose that I would feel inferior and insecure. I would worry that others look down on me with condescension and I might withdraw from socializing.
If I were in the bottom of the ladder, It would make it really hard for me to even show or step into the same room as my pears.

Yesterday I attended my 5-year college reunion, it was humiliating. All I realized was that I have been left behind in my career and prominence, I feel like a disappointment. While everyone else has progressed in their social and financial life I am struggling to keep up and I feel like I am being left behind.
If I was at the bottom of the later, I would have so much regret in terms of the relationships I made in college

If I was at the bottom, I may feel terrible and even feel cynical. I may think that I do not deserve this. But, because I had similar experience in middle school and became generally not caring to much about the my influence/status at school, I might be quite resilient to the situation and become motivated to graduate as soon as possible.

I entered the room and saw a majority of people in Tuxedos. I looked down at my torn jeans and sneakers and wondered when was this decided. I couldn't not hold up a conversation that many of my friends and I could during college. Nobody played video games. Nobody had time to watch NBA or the Premier League. They were all busy in their work and hustle for money. While I was stilling scouting for a job, some of my acquaintances were talking about buying or partnering with other successful companies. I felt that money wise I was a bit behind, but deep down do I really want to live a life full of stress and and luxury, because everything for that matter is not permanent. Nothing will last.
I knew the reunion would be awful and I was right. No one knew my name, I felt ostracized, and the people haven't changed at all. So arrogant and entitled
I would feel ashamed and lonely
I would be sad that I had no respect after being at Wake for 4 years.
i would feel like a let down, that i haven't accomplished anything

I would honestly just want to see old friends and meet other people I didn't know that well during college. A part of me would be embarrassed if I wasn't doing well economically. If I had no job and people asked what I did, I would most likely say my last job because I'd be too embarrassed to admit I failed. I would act warm and friendly to everyone, but deep down I would be wondering what they think of me now.
I feel like I shouldn't be here. No one remembers who I am or wants to listen to what I have to say. I feel like my opinions don't mean much and no one even knows I am here.
I would likely be kind of shy coming back to a place where I had such a low standing.

Attending the 5-year college reunion was the worst thing of my life. At this point in my life I don't feel like myself, I think everybody is judging me and I just want to be left alone. But I thought my college friends would make things better, but it didn't.
unaccomplished, self-conscious

Dear Diary, I feel like everyone has passed me by. All of my peers who made me feel inferior in my time at Wake Forest, and that has not changed wince we graduated. I feel like I have gone nowhere in life, and everyone else is flourishing.
I would feel bad

I would feel inferior. I would tell myself that these things don't matter and that I still have time to achieve the things I lust for but I would still feel internally down. I would still act with complete composure with no shame or angst but would still feel different inside. I would feel happy for those that I knew worked really hard and came from the bottom. I would probably feel angst towards those who had everything set up but I couldn't blame theme completely because I would know that I had plentiful resources and benefits.

I would feel somehow shamed to appeared on the scene, even if I know the people besides me are friends with me 5 years ago and we've lose contact since, I might not going to revisit them since I don't feel enough pride to be among them anymore.

If I were to attend my 5-year college reunion and I was at the bottom of the ladder, I would come back uneasy. I would see everyone else in my class doing so well, but not myself. This would make me self conscious and sad at the meeting. I would be very timid, bu tI would also still say hello to everyone that I have not seen in 5 years.
I would feel a little ashamed realizing how little impact I had on those around me.
worthless, scared of others' opinions, alone/lonely
I am a failure. I went to such a prestigious school that offered various opportunities yet I have somehow still at the bottom. I did work hard and tried my best. It doesn’t feel fair.

I would be overly self-conscious and would continuously feel left out. I would feel like it was not my home, but a school I attended for a few years. I would awkwardly try to hold surface level conversations with others while not really wanting to be in them, but didn't have anything better to do. I would feel lost and out of place.

If I were at the bottom of the ladder, I would feel as if I had a very low-paying job that isn't challenging or interesting compared to everyone else at the reunion. I probably would not have had a lot of experiences in life and would be sad or depressed with the state of my life. I would most likely act shy or reserved instead of how outgoing and happy the people at the top of the ladder are. I would think that the people at the top of the ladder are much more superior and happier than I am and I would wish as if I had their life.
I would feel unhappy and not confident. I would be more shy and less willing to share details about my life.

Yesterday I went to my 5-year college reunion. I saw the students that I graduated with, who I have not seen all these 5 years. I didn't want to attend the event but ended up enjoying seeing how everyone's future ended up being. I'm happy to see that I'm more successful and have used my time better than everyone else. I won't be attending another one of these reunions though, I only came for the free food but I don't want to put my efforts into showing my spirit for this school anymore. They are just looking for my donations.

I felt like a disappointment today. I watched as people caught up with old friends, teammates, and peers. No one remembered me. I wish I had done more to impact those around me. I wish there had been someone around me back then to push me more, to encourage me to influence people's lives in a positive way like I know I can. I had a great opportunity to build connections and to network, but I didn't capitalize on those chances.

If I were at the bottom of the ladder at my five year reunion, meaning that I had no perceived respect, success, or admiration, I would feel very incomplete. A large part in coming to Wake Forest was to set myself up for greatness in my future career, so I would feel as if I failed my past self.

My reunion was yesterday back at school. I feel so inadaquate compared to my classmates. There are all set in their current jobs or in med school close to finishing up. It took me too long to figure out what I wanted to do and now I am back to where I was when I first entered college. Single, living with my parents, unable to afford groceries and working a minimum wage job as I apply for grad schools. I feel like I have wasted my prime 5 years out of school with silly travel and not enough work and effort. I am even at a loss for what grad program I want to apply to.

Going to my 5-year college reunion has really made me feel worthless. I knew that I have not achieved a great deal of success since graduating from college, but seeing how successful and well off everyone else is feels like a kick to the face. I was embarrassed to share the details of my life and job because they felt so trivial in comparison to what my peers were accomplishing. I am struggling to keep a job, while many of my peers are now running successful start-ups or holding prominent positions at fortune 500 companies. As soon as I shared the details of my life with my peers, it seemed as if they began scoffing at me and my opinions were no longer important. It was all just another reminder of what my parents tell me every time I see them: I wasted a Wake Forest education, spending an insanely large sum of money just to end up worse off than the majority of people who went to state schools.

I would have only talked to the relatively small number people that I got to know closely during my time there. I would assume that the majority of the people wouldn't really care about interacting with me. I would feel left out of the larger group dynamics and not be able to relate to many of my peers.

I would be really awkward and ashamed. Other people are making big progress in their career, and why I am at the bottom of the ladder. I may even question whether if it is family background that makes other people ahead of me.

I saw everyone from Wake today. They're all doing well. Way better than me, and all I can think is How did I let this happen? How did I not think I needed to step it up and push harder? How do these people know what they're doing and where they're going? I feel like I can't compete with anyone.
NA

I would feel as though I wasted an opportunity at Wake Forest to be a leader and make a different. I think it might feel very lonely and despairing. Being on the bottom of that ladder means that there was a lack of connection made at Wake, and I would feel very sad and disappointed about that.

Yesterday I attended my 5-year college reunion. I went alone and everyone I encountered from my graduating class either didn't talk to me or remember my name. I was embarrassed to be there as everyone around me was talking about their "great" lives and all the amazing job opportunities they've already experienced. Looking back at my time at Wake Forest, I have many regrets, as I did not apply myself or take school seriously.

I feel like I have completely let the opportunities in my life pass me by.  I have lost my friends out of selfishness and greed and feel extremely lonely and unaccomplished.  It is a truly heartbreaking combination.

The lack of respect or attention I receive is painful to see, as it is clearly different from the average person. Because of this lack of respect, I have no motivation to either support others or regard myself highly.
I would feel uncomfortable and not successful compared to my peers. I would also feel out of place and would want to try harder to get to the "top" of the ladder.

I would be extremely upset if I was at the bottom of the ladder. I'm extremely disappointed in myself, and I'd be very worried what my parents, teachers, and friends think of me. I know I am a hard worker, so wonder if something big happened in my life that changed this.

After returning from my 5-year college reunion, I feel very low compared to my peers. Despite all having the same education and opportunities, they all earned more respect and are more successful than me. I felt like I didn't have a voice compared to them and that we aren't equals. I feel much less important than all of them. I don't understand how we all started at the same point yet all ended up so differently.

If i were at the bottom I would be almost mad to be at the reunion and would not want to talk or interact with anyone from my class as i wouldn't care for them. Overall being disrespectful and ignorant towards the school and others.

I attended to my 5-year college reunion. It was horrible, we all payed to get the best education yet I failed to succeed. I went in and talked to everyone who I haven't seen in years. When they asked "what new projects have you been part of?" or "What do you do for a living?" I kept it short and sweet. I would say "nothing much, just living life to the fullest what about you?" I know that I am happy and that is all that matters.

If I was at the bottom of the ladder I would feel as if I have a lower paying job, and be unable to contribute into some of the conversations of other students in the class. Along with that, I feel like I would be working in a job sphere separate from the "typical" higher bracket jobs. I also would feel like the other students would judge me for not being at their same level.

My low self esteem would validate itself by comparing the achievements of others to my struggles. I would think that I am a failure. I would feel very self conscious. I would probably feel embarrassed and not talk to many people.

At the bottom of the ladder, I'd probably feel pretty out of place. I might feel a little resentful and upset with the people surrounding me knowing they took advantage of what was offered to them during college. I'd think I wasn't as good as the rest of the group and not as fortunate or well off.

Dear Diary, Today was my five year college reunion. Growing up, I always envisioned showing up to the reunion very successful. I wanted to have influence and be settled in my life. However, that is not the case. I am disappointed in myself. I thought within the last five years I would have accomplished something with my life. I am embarassed to be at this reunion. I an ashamed that my peers are doing better than me and do not have anything to show for the loads of money I spent on college.

Man, it is really unfortunate that I am was so disrespected. I am sure that I would be pretty sad. Wake Forest is a school where people go with the intent of having success in their futures. We also learn that success comes in many different forms, so to be viewed with such disrespect would mean my life probably has not been too great since graduation.

Personally, I would feel extremely out of a place and somewhat embarrassed almost. I would not feel very comfortable attending the college reunion as a matter of fact. I would tend to be somewhat quiet and stray from conversation. I would most likely hold brief conversations with people who I knew during my time at the university and my interactions would be limited. If people asked me how I have been I would probably hesitate to answer and not know what to say.

Looking at all these people around me, dressed in tuxedos and suits, wearing diamond rings and luxurious watches, I felt incredibly out of place. They started to chat, complimenting each other on the things they have done in and beyond college, while I sat in the corner sipping my drink alone. But this was not the worst; if they notice me, they might start laughing at me, mocking me for being a loner in college, hiding in my dorm, feeding off of university money. Even the professors don't know I existed, they say. I felt so uncomfortable, I just wanted to dig a hole and jump in. It's not my fault I'm not like the others.
I would be disappointed and feel embarrassed to attend in a way because I'd invested time and money into my time there.

If I were at the bottom of the latter I would feel like a failure. I would feel as though I wasted my parents' money that they used to pay for my education here and that I did not make the most of the opportunities and resources that were provided to me. I would have a feeling of major regret and probably be overwhelmed with sadness.

I feel like I am being judged by everyone I saw at the reunion. I think that people do not care that I had gone or that I made any true friends at my time in Wake. I had stayed composed but did not talk to many people because I feel like they wouldn't want to talk to me. I was anxious the entire time and did not have fun because no one seemed to care that I had even attended Wake.
I felt as if I didn't belong at this reunion with people who were all much wealthier and better off than I. I felt embarrassed that they been much more successful in the real world than I had.

Yesterday I had my 5 year reunion. I feel terrible about myself. I went to a great school and somehow didn't go anywhere in life. I don't have a good job and am not in a good graduate school. I don't know what I am going to do. My parents spent so much money sending me here and no one even respected me because I didn't make any money and am not successful.

I would feel forgotten, neglected, undervalued, and jealous, for my peers are better off than me. I would feel self-conscious and embarrassed, as my life is more of a struggle than theirs. I do not have anything going for me, and I would think that it only makes things worse to be in the same room as my successful peers.

If I was at the bottom of the ladder after going to a prestigious, private college, I would be seriously concerned, as my parents pay immense amounts of money for me to attend college and be well off later in my life. To rise from the bottom of the ladder, I would continue to pick up jobs and do the best I could to become more motivated.

Upon returning from my five year college reunion, I am devastated to see those around me doing so well compared to me. I think that I don't see the opportunity to grow and gain the admiration that those around me have. I regret the decisions that got me in this place and know that I will not be able to grow from this given how no one gives me the time of day. This really sucks.

Yesterday, I attended my 5 year college reunion and it was so embarrassing. Somehow all of us attended the same school for 4 years and I am worse off than everyone. I received no respect from my ex peers and I am so sad to have been so unsuccessful in comparison.

Yesterday I attended my five-year college reunion. I feel as if there is something wrong with me; what is my purpose and influence on my peers and surrounding community? I feel discouraged, but hope to use this anger and frustration and turn it into a positive, productive lifestyle. I want to have goals. I want to feel like I made a difference. This difference starts with me.

I would fell disappointed in myself that I got such a great education at Wake Forest and failed to take that into the real world. I would definitely do a lot of reflecting about how/where things went wrong and try to rationalize why I am at the bottom place on the ladder.

If I were at the bottom of the ladder, I probably would really feel diminished, especially in comparison to all of those people I just saw that had successful jobs and lives and I had the same resources and tools yet chose not to use them. I would be disappointed yet hopefully in the end inspired and driven.
I would feel small and unaccomplished. I would probably be quiet and reserved, not talking to many people, embarrassed of myself. I probably would not want to go to the reunion because I am ashamed.
I know all of these people yet none of them know me. I spent 4-years with these people, eating in the same spaces, walking to and from class yet they walk past me as if they don't know me.
I would be insecure, and unsure of myself. I wouldn't work as hard and I would be scared to speak up in classes.

If I were at the bottom of the ladder, I would feel dissapointed personally that I did not take advantage of all of the great opportunities and networks of people that Wake has to offer. I would think of myself as one who became too distracted by other worldly things to truly focus on growing into the best version of myself I could be.

I think I would be welcoming and nice to everyone regardless of there social status. I grew up in a very privileged community and wealthy family but I never let that consume me. I did not like to let it show and I welcomed everyone the same. I didn't think I was superior to anyone because I don't have that right. If I was at the bottom place in the ladder I would be very insecure but I would try to look past those little ideas that stood out to me. After all, it was my high school reunion and by now I should have learned to grow despite my space on the ladder.

At my 5-year college reunion, I felt worthless and unsuccessful. I did not go out of my way to tell people what I did for a living, as I was embarrassed and felt judged whenever I did explain what I did. I felt sad and dumb.

Being at the bottom of the ladder would make me feel inferior to my peers, and make me question my accomplishments or lack thereof after graduating. I would go out of my way to make new connections to increase my spot on the ladder.

I am sad and upset that I am not respected by my peers. I worked hard at school and am mad that no one likes me. I am going to make an effort to reach out to my peers and give them reasons to like me and respect me.

I'd feel really disappointed and embarrassed. I wouldn't want to tell people much about my life if I was at the bottom of this ladder, because I would imagine that most of my class would be in or around the top of it.

I would highly doubt whether I would attend the reunion or not if I was at the bottom place on the ladder. But since I have been there, I would not enjoy the reunion, and possibly curse most of the people I met during the event.

I would feel uncomfortable and out of place knowing people respect me for the way I was in college. I would feel regret for not trying to make a difference during my time at school. I think part of me would want to try and fix my reputation, but I wouldn't be able to bring myself to do it knowing how they felt.

If I were at the bottom, I would feel awkward among my peers because most Wake Forest graduates are successful. It be at the bottom of the ladder and to mingle with everyone else who is close to the top of the ladder would be a weird experience from my point of view.
Ashamed and embarassed

I think that if I were at the bottom of the ladder in 5-years I would feel ashamed. I would feel like I wasted the opportunity and privilege that I had and ruined my life. I would think I wasted my childhood and teenage years just to fail.

After seeing everyone at the reunion yesterday it is safe to say my confidence has been completely shot through. It is tough to see everyone that i have graduated with in the past living their dream lives as i am struggling to make ends meet. From this day forward i never want to feel like this again, i will do everything in my power to better myself and to gain my own self respect back. I am willing to put in the work to be even better than before, now i just have to grind till i have nothing left to give.
Seeing how we've all gone different ways is exciting but somewhat disheartening. I feel disappointed comparing myself to those I used to live such a similar life to.

It was weird to be back with my class at the reunion. During my time at Wake I did not feel respected by my classmates. Yesterday, it did not matter if you were an athlete or a nerd, it did not matter if you were in the hardest classes or easiest classes. All that people asked me was what is your current job? Where are you living? The judgements on achievement and success were still there five years later. I felt that people did not care about my well being only about my current income. I acted brief with them as they had not made me feel good in college nor did they make me feel good at the reunion. I thought that they had not changed at all.
I would be very upset for not being in a good mindset
I feel embarrassed because after these five years, I've now seen the great passions of so many people that have developed over these years, meanwhile I feel like I'm lacking drive.
Today I felt really insecure, and was watching what I was saying to everyone. It felt like everyone else was having a great time and I was bothering everyone.

Hey girl. I know that right now it seems as though you are in a valley. However, know that God is a God that will never leave you nor forsake you. Keep praying that God will give you the desires of your heart and that your desires will match with His will for your life.
I would be a little embarrassed about where I'd be in comparison to other, but I'd also feel guilty that I didn't make better decisions to give myself a better life
I would be saddened and hopefully motivated to do better.
Dear journal, I feel ashamed of where I am today. All of my peers are much more respected and admired. I wish I could change where I was.

I would hate everyone at the reunion. If I see people who have succeeded in life at this event, I would be annoyed with them, especially if they are kind to everyone. I would still have the high school mentality that I'm better than everyone else and would have no respect for anyone who had attended the reunion. I would have lost all of my college friends and would have felt horrible to see them again because I would have no respect for them. I would act and feel better than everyone else and would be completely selfish. This is how I would act if I was at the bottom.
To me the bottom of the ladder would feel lonely, and isolating and I would think that I wouldn't feel fulfilled.

I just had my 5 year reunion and everyone is doing so much better than I am. I feel really terrible. Just knowing that we went to the same school and got the same education but they're doing a lot better is difficult.

I feel ashamed and incompetent. I had five years after college to make something of myself and instead I have not moved an inch on the ladder. I acted reserved and unconfident in front of the people I went to school with for five years whom I once had the years of my life with.

I feel worthless, everyone else has gone on to do great things and yet I did not accomplish any of my goals. I didn't even work towards those goals. I am not financially stable and my mental health has only deteriorated. I am at the opposite of where I wanted to be.

I would feel miserable. I'm a competitor and push myself by comparing myself to others. I would be depressed seeing everyone who received the same education as me thrive while I failed. I want everyone to succeed, but if everyone is doing better, that means I'm doing something wrong.
have no respect from others, no friends, low self-esteem and do badly on study, feel lonely

I feel as though I've completely failed myself. Seeing the people I went to school with and where they now are has helped me gauge how terrible of a position I am now in, especially in comparison to those who were once my peers and equals.

The feeling of being unsuccessful was unusually apparent as I saw my past classmates, friends, and mentors yesterday. Comparing myself to them, I have fallen short in the achievement of my goals that I so ambitiously set in front of myself five years ago. I struggled to act as if everything I had dreamed of was still in reach, but once I saw how well everyone else was faring, it was hard to stifle my disappointment.
I will consider my life as a failure and have no courage to talk to other classmates at the reunion.

If I were to be at the bottom place on the ladder, I would feel frustration, but not hopeless. Knowing me, I would have been someone who spent my 4 years working hard to obtain my life-long dream. But, if certain circumstances were to have prevented me from obtaining my goal in those 4 years, I would have hope and work hard until my dream is achieved. I might feel frustrated because it's taking time, but I wouldn't give up and instead make the best of my situation because all obstacles will strengthen my character and help build me until I am ready to take on what I've been preparing for.

After my 5-year college reunion, I  would feel very low and down about myself after seeing what everyone else in my class has accomplished since graduation. I  would probably not have spoken very much to people other than my close friends at the reunion, and I  would probably not feel very good about going to more reunions in the future. However I   think that I would also begin to think about the ways I could change how I view myself and how I could improve my life, my self worth, and gain the respect of others at Wake.
I would not feel comfortable is I were at the bottom place on the ladder and will think why I didn't try better

I feel extremely dishonored, and unwanted in society. I feel like my college education was not worth it, as attending college was supposed to be an experience where I could make lifelong friends, gain respect and lead a happy life. But now I do not know how to feel.

I am extremely uncomfortable and embarrassed at this reunion. It is disheartening to know that I had the same educational resources as my peers, and did not take advantage of them. I feel extremely guilty and shameful that my parents paid for my education and believed that its benefits would outweigh the cost. I feel like a failure. Knowing that my peers view me in a low regard makes me paranoid about my normal behaviors, as I feel judged. I am motivated to change my ways, however, as I do not want this feeling of failure to persist.

Today I realized that I have not accomplished my expectations for myself. I feel insecure, insignificant, and lonely. I cannot help but compare myself to everyone around me and wonder what I should have done differently. I am totally disappointed.
I think I would feel alone, worthless, and upset.

In the grand scheme of things, it is honestly surprising that no one awaited for my arrival. I went to my 5-year college reunion last night and I felt like there were soul suckers out there peering into my soul and glaring at me intensely. I tried to catch up with my old college mates and my roommates and they have flat out ignored me. Saw some of my professors, made some small talk, but it seemed like they were uninterested in knowing how far I made it after graduation. No one seemed to care who I was or I have become. I sat at a table with random people that I have never met during my four years of college, made some small talk with them, but apparently they gave me the cold shoulder after realizing who I was. Tough luck, they're missing out on who I've become.
nothing has changed since college. i haven't moved out of my parents house, i don't have a carrer, and im not enjoying my life

I would be pretty upset, seeing how everyone besides me have had successful jobs, relationships, and other good things in their life. I would try and make people think my life was better than it really is, but deep down would feel unimpressed with myself.

I sat in the corner the entire time, feeling hopeless and embaressed, before deciding it was best to make an "Irish exit" as they call it. I don't know what I did wrong, but all I know is that everyone else seems to have everything in order, everyone except me.
